Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/Presenting
Object: The act of presenting materials to a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/toHouse
Object: Relates an act of making materials available to a House, to the House in which they are made available.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/
Object: A model describing the means of making material available to a House, for example: by presenting, laying or depositing.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/MakingAvailable
Object: The act of making materials available to a House or to a House by means of its library.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/House
Object: A parliamentary House, for example: the House of Lords.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/inSession
Object: Relates an act of making materials available to a House, to the session in which they are made available.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/madeAvailableOn
Object: Relates an act of making materials available to a House, to the date on which they are made available.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/Depositing
Object: The act of depositing materials into the library of a House.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/Session
Object: The period during which Parliament is convened. The first session of a parliament begins on the same day as the parliament period: this date is given in the dissolution proclamation at the end of the previous parliament. The session ends on the day given in a subsequent prorogation proclamation. Subsequent sessions within the parliament begin and end on dates given in prorogation proclamations. The last session of a parliament ends with prorogation followed by dissolution. A session typically lasts for one year. Session periods are the same across both Houses.

Subject: http://parliament.uk/ontologies/making-available/Laying
Object: The act of presenting a paper and supporting documents into either House. Papers may be laid in both Houses on the same day.
